   <par align="l" li="0" ri="0" iln="0">
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Curium is a silvery, dense metal. It is a synthetic, transuranic element, i.e. an artificially prepared radioactive element. It was obtained in 1944 by the American researchers: Glenn T. Seaborg, Ralph A. James and Albert Ghiorso by the bombardment of plutonium-239 with </text>
      <text fn="Symbol" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="2">alpha</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">-particles (helium nuclei). The most stable isotope of curium is curium-247, with a half-life of 4.78 · </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">10</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="16" fc="1163500" fs="b" fa="1" charset="238">7</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">  years. Curium is chemically reactive; reacts with chlorine, hydrogen and nitrogen; corrodes in air. </text>
   </par>
   <par align="l" li="0" ri="0" iln="0">
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">The most stable compounds of curium are the oxides and halides. The following compounds are known: curium(IV) oxide </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">– Cm</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">, curium(III) oxide – C</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">m</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">, curium(III) bromide – CmB</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">r</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">, curium(III) chloride  – CmC</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">l</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">, curium(III) iodide – Cm</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">I</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> etc. Curium is a harmful element, due to its strong radioactivity and its accumulation in bone tissue. It was named in honour of Marie Sklodowska-Curie and her husband, Pierre Curie.</text>
   </par>
